          <p>Welcome Back!</p>
          
          <p>We are getting closer to running your game. </p>
      
          <p>This time please do the following:</p>
          <p>Click on File.</p>
           <p>Click on Build Settings (not Build and Run, we are not ready for that just yet).</p>
           <p>Build Settings should then pop up. You should see on the left hand side
           an area called Platform.</p>
           <p>This area is where we decide what we want our game to run on. You should see that 
           PC, Mac, & Linux Standalone, as well as Android have items on the right hand side. If you click on
           PS4 or iOS, they should only have a message asking for you to download their module.
           That is because we have only downloaded the Android version and the PC version is default.</p>
          <p>Click on Android and at the bottom of the information for Android, click on the button that says
          Switch Platform. </p>
          
          <p>When that is done, click Build and Run. It will now ask you for a file name. Save this file as 
          MyFirstGameTestComputer.</p>
          <p>Click on Save.</p>
          
          <p>Now let's wait for it to run. You should get an error saying there is now Android Device plugged in.</p>
          <p>As long as that is your only error in this step, then you are good. </p>
          
          <p>If not and you get an error saying Android SDK is not working, then click out
          of Build Settings, click on Edit on the Menu Bar, and then click on Preferences.</p>
          
          <p>Make sure that you are searching in External Tools. </p>
          <p>Android SDK Tools Installed with Unity should be clicked.</p>
          <p>Unclick it for the moment and check to see if everything looks correct. 
          The file path, or the path that the computer knows to take when it is looking for 
          a specific item, should look like this.</p>
          
          <p>C:\Program Files\Unity\Hub\Editor\2019.3.1f1\Editor\Data\PlaybackEngines\AndroidPlayer\SDK</p>
          
          <p>If everything looks good, then you should be fine.</p>
          <p>If it does not, and you see AndroidPlayer/SDK, click on on / and replace it with \. </p>
          <p>They look very similar, but unfortunately it changes the path the computer looks at. 
          So instead of the computer looking inside the AndroidPlayer folder, it is looking at AndroidPlayer and stopping.
          This is causing for the SDK not to be found. </p>
          
          <p>If this is the issue you had, change it, exit out of External Tools, and try Build and Run again. </p>
          
          <p>Great! Everything should be working. Go onto the next tutorial for the next step. </p>

